# NFS Configuration

## Objective

To configure a Network File System (NFS) server for sharing directories between Linux systems with controlled access.

---

## Tools Used

* Linux (RHEL / CentOS)
* NFS Server (nfs-utils)

---

## Installation

```bash
sudo yum install nfs-utils -y
```

---

## Start and Enable Service

```bash
sudo systemctl start nfs-server
sudo systemctl enable nfs-server
```

---

## Create Shared Directory

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /nfs_share
sudo chmod 777 /nfs_share
```

---

## Configure Exports File

```bash
sudo vi /etc/exports
```

Add:

```
/nfs_share *(rw,sync,no_root_squash)
```

---

## Apply Configuration

```bash
sudo exportfs -rav
```

---

## Configure Firewall

```bash
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=nfs
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
```

---

## Client Side Mount

```bash
sudo mount <server-ip>:/nfs_share /mnt
```

---

## Result

* Centralized file sharing established
* Multiple clients can access shared directory
* Permissions managed effectively

---

## Real-World Use Case

* Shared storage in enterprise environments
* Backup and data synchronization
* Centralized access for multiple servers
